FT  25 FEB 94 / UK Company News: CEGF placing oversubscribed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The institutional placing for the Central European Growth Fund, an
investment trust to be managed by CS First Boston, was oversubscribed at
Dollars 150m (Pounds 103m). Up to Dollars 50m more is expected to be raised
from the public offer, which opens today.
The fund, which although dollar denominated will have a London quote, will
invest in the Czech Republic, Hungary and Poland, with up to 20 per cent
elsewhere in central Europe.
The main focus will be on small to medium-sized companies (Dollars 20m to
Dollars 300m capitalisation) listed on the Prague, Warsaw and Budapest stock
exchanges, but a proportion will also be invested in companies expected to
gain a listing within two years.
Mr Charles Harman, of CS First Boston, described these economies as 'not so
much emerging markets as re-emerging markets' with a strong industrial
tradition and low wage costs.
CS First Boston has been active in the region for several years, including
managing Dollars 750m of funds for local clients.
Investment of money raised through the issue will take place gradually over
the next six to 12 months, to avoid pushing up share prices with a flood of
new money. This will also allow the fund to take advantage of privatisations
expected in the near future.
Ordinary shares are offered at Dollars 1, with one warrant attached to every
five shares. The impact of issue expenses will mean that ordinary shares
will have an initial net asset value of 96.2 cents.
The public offer closes on March 11, and dealings in the shares and warrants
is expected to start on March 21.
</TEXT>
