<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Strong end to year as Telegraph rises 36%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A strong final quarter helped The Telegraph lift 1993 pre-tax profits 36 per
cent from Pounds 44.3m to Pounds 60.2m. Excluding one-off items, pre-tax
profits were 15.5 per cent higher at Pounds 53.7m.
A final dividend of 7.5p is proposed to give a total of 13p (11p), a rise of
18 per cent.
Mr Joe Cooke, managing director, said that the trend of stronger advertising
revenue had continued into the current year. The shares rose 7p to 587p,
compared with the flotation price of 325p in July 1992.
The group, which publishes the Daily and Sunday Telegraph in the UK, also
has a 25 per cent stake in John Fairfax Holdings, the Australian newspaper
group, and a 9.4 per cent stake in Southam, the Canadian publisher. Nearly
20 per cent of pre-tax profit comes from outside the UK, Mr Conrad Black,
chairman, said.
During 1993, newspaper advertising revenue rose 8 per cent while circulation
revenue increased by almost 6 per cent. Mr Cooke said that the price of the
Monday to Friday Daily Telegraph had been increased in February last year,
but the Saturday and Sunday papers prices had not risen in the autumn as was
usual. The Saturday edition's price was 'the next candidate' for an
increase, he said.
About 53 per cent of revenue came from advertising, a recovery from recent
years, but well below the two thirds contributed in the peak year of 1989.
Group turnover rose 8 per cent to Pounds 255.7m (Pounds 237.2m) for
operating profits up from Pounds 37.5m, after Pounds 2.2m of float costs, to
Pounds 42.9m.
The sale of a stake in Trinity International Holdings in February
contributed a profit of Pounds 6.5m.
Associates more than doubled to Pounds 12.7m (Pounds 5.9m) largely because
of the increase in the Fairfax stake.
There was a Pounds 2.8m worsening in the interest position, as a credit of
Pounds 900,000 turned to a debit of Pounds 1.9m. During 1993 The Telegraph
increased its stake in Fairfax from 15 per cent, at a cost of Pounds 74m and
acquired the Southam stake for Pounds 66m. As a result total borrowings rose
from Pounds 40.5m to Pounds 104m. However, taking account of cash of Pounds
9.5m, gearing at the year end was 31 per cent.
The tax rate rose to 30.9 per cent (27.5 per cent). Earnings per share were
higher at 30.6p (23.8p) or 27.4p (23.8p), excluding the investment profit.
COMMENT
The cycle is beginning to work in The Telegraph's favour and 1994 should see
further good growth in advertising. Meanwhile, Fairfax is proving a good
investment, though the cycle there is perhaps two years behind that in the
UK. Later on the Southam stake should also contribute as it also responds to
the cost-cutting. With profits this year expected to rise to about Pounds
65m, the prospective p/e is about 17. Suspicions over the 68 per cent stake
held by Mr Black's Hollinger group seem to have been dispelled and the
shares could continue to outperform.
Fairfax results, Page 34
</TEXT>
