<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Towry Law at Pounds 565,000 after listing
costs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Towry Law, the chain of independent financial advisers which floated last
November, returned pre-tax profits of Pounds 565,000 for the six months to
December 31 after meeting the Pounds 237,000 costs of listing.
The comparable figure for 1992 was Pounds 42,000.
Turnover rose to Pounds 10.9m, an improvement of 29 per cent over last
time's Pounds 8.44m.
Mr Cecil Law, chairman, said that as trading last year was 'difficult' in
the first half and strong in the second six months, the increase in the
current second half was unlikely to be as large.
An interim dividend of 1.5p is declared from earnings of 1.9p (0.2p).
The financial services industry is currently the subject of an investigation
into faulty advice on pension transfers. Independent financial advisers have
been among those criticised, but Towry Law said it had not advised on any
transfers involving opt-outs from final salary schemes, and its involvement
generally in transfers from public sector schemes was minor.
Pensions advisory activities are responsible for the smallest proportion of
turnover of the company's three divisions, after financial planning and
insurance broking.
