<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Royal Insurance back in the black at Pounds
143m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Royal Insurance, one of the UK's largest composite insurers, is back in the
black after three years of heavy losses.
The company reported pre-tax profits of Pounds 143m, against a deficit of
Pounds 27m last year and losses of nearly Pounds 600m since 1990.
A final dividend of 7.5p is proposed, compared with 5p in 1992 and a
forecast of 6.5p at the time of the rights issue last year.
Like Commercial Union and Guardian Royal Exchange, Royal's turnround hinged
on a marked improvement in trading conditions in the UK.
UK underwriting losses were reduced from Pounds 259m to Pounds 15m, with
most lines of business underwritten profitably.
Mr Richard Gamble, chief executive, singled out a particularly good
performance by The Insurance Service, the Bristol-based telephone motor
insurer, which increased its sales by 15 per cent, made profits of Pounds 5m
and now has 370,000 motor policyholders.
Royal increased its UK premium income to Pounds 1.62bn (Pounds 1.55bn), but
shed some market share in home and private motor insurance, where income
fell to Pounds 605m (Pounds 615m) and Pounds 231m (Pounds 239m)
respectively.
Profits in Canada fell slightly from Pounds 23m to Pounds 21m. The US also
showed a decline, from Pounds 24m to Pounds 15m, while other territories
edged ahead to Pounds 40m (Pounds 38m). Reserves to meet potential claims
stemming from US pollution were increased by Dollars 37m to Dollars 248m
(Pounds 170m).
Higher than expected losses of Pounds 87m at Royal Re, where claims
continued to mount on business underwritten in earlier years, were despite
the subsidiary's withdrawal from most markets.
Losses of Pounds 16m (Pounds 33m) by Royal's estate agency subsidiary also
marred the picture. Life assurance profits rose to Pounds 31m (Pounds 29m).
Overall last year, premium income at Royal's general insurance subsidiary
rose to Pounds 4.04bn (Pounds 3.75bn). Underwriting losses fell to Pounds
371m (Pounds 588m). Investment income increased to Pounds 521m (Pounds
486m), and income from associated undertakings rose to Pounds 27m (Pounds
21m).
COMMENT
On several counts the immediate future for Royal looks rosy. Mortgage
indemnity and reinsurance losses should fall further this year. Much of
Royal's exposure to the personal motor market, where rates could begin to
soften, is through its very competitive direct telephone-based insurance
subsidiary. Pre-tax profits of Pounds 290m for 1994 appear well within the
company's grasp, giving a prospective multiple of only 7. Investors will
have been encouraged by the rate of yesterday's dividend increase. A pay-out
of 10p next year puts the shares on a prospective yield of 4.4, reducing the
gap with higher yielding rivals. The main question mark concerns Royal's
well-known exposure to potentially substantial US pollution claims. The
company says its reserves are adequate. If you accept that, it becomes
difficult to justify the sizeable discount to net asset value and the shares
look cheap.
</TEXT>
