<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / Issue by RJR Nabisco to boost war chest
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RJR Nabisco the US tobacco and food group best known for its Camel cigarette
brand, yesterday surprised the stock market by announcing a Dollars 2bn
(Pounds 1.3bn) share issue that could signal the start of an acquisition
spree.
It plans to offer 300m shares, called preferred equity redemption stock,
which will pay a quarterly cash dividend for three years, then convert into
ordinary shares on a one-for-one basis.
Mr Charles Harper, chairman and chief executive, said the main reason for
the share issue was to cut debt from 44.5 per cent to 43 per cent of
capitalisation in line with a five-year plan.
But only Dollars 500m of the proceeds would be applied specifically to debt
reduction, Mr Harper said. The remaining Dollars 1.5bn could be used for one
or more significant corporate transactions, such as a joint venture, merger,
acquisition, divestiture, asset spin-off, or recapitalisation. 'We have no
specific transaction on the table, but this war chest will help us look at
things we couldn't look at before,' Mr Harper said. 'There are a number of
interesting possibilities. We have been talking to people and will continue
to talk to people, to find investment opportunities.'
Mr Harper said RJR Nabisco would consider any acquisition that provided a 20
per cent return on equity and fell within its 'area of general competence'.
This could include its growth areas of international tobacco, international
food, and domestic food - but not the domestic tobacco market, which is in
decline.
At the end of 1993, RJR Nabisco had Dollars 12.4bn of debt, largely
resulting from the record-breaking Dollars 25bn leveraged buy-out of the
company organised by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts, the Wall Street buy-out
specialist, in 1989.
Last summer - shortly after Philip Morris, the rival US tobacco and food
group, prompted a damaging cigarette price war in the domestic market by
cutting the price of its Marlboro cigarettes - RJR Nabisco attempted to
raise Dollars 1.5bn by issuing 'smoke free' shares pegged to the performance
of its non-tobacco businesses.
The offer was dropped when not enough takers could be found. Wall Street
thought RJR Nabisco was asking too much for the shares because it had sold
substantial parts of its international food business to help pay off the
buy-out debt, leaving it over-exposed to the highly competitive US market.
Yesterday's announcement - and RJR Nabisco's specific reference to using the
funds for a recapitalisation - prompted speculation the company may revive
the scheme, but RJR Nabisco said it had no plans to do so.
</TEXT>
