<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / Universities turn to investment bank to help raise private
funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK universities have appointed European Capital, the investment banking
boutique, to draw up a blueprint for them to raise finance from the capital
markets.
They plan to use the extra funds for academic capital projects, such as new
libraries and lecture theatres. The committee of vice-chancellors and
principals last year estimated that the universities' total need for extra
capital spending in addition to that provided by the government was Pounds
3.2bn.
Mr John Avery, head of estate management for the government's English higher
education funding council, which will be paying European Capital's fees
jointly with the vice-chancellors, said: 'We see the partnership as becoming
more and more dominated by the universities because clearly there is not
enough public money generated through us to support their capital needs.'
The first funds could be raised by the end of this year, provided European
Capital does not find any serious legal or technical problems. The company's
brief is to prepare a blueprint for a financial vehicle company in which a
syndicate of universities would raise money.
The scheme forms a significant step in the government's private finance
initiative, which is aiming to attract private funds into public sector
infrastructure projects. It takes advantage of freedoms given to
universities to borrow against their assets.
By raising money through a vehicle company that will spread the risk for
borrowers across several projects, universities hope to borrow on more
favourable terms than would be available normally.
Their borrowing capacity against assets funded by the government is still
limited, so that the costs of repaying the loan must not exceed 7 per cent
of their income. However, the funding councils will relax this rule except
where it is plain that a university's financial health could be damaged.
European Capital aims to produce a blueprint on how the financial vehicle
company should be formed by the end of April.
Editorial Comment, Page 23
</TEXT>
