FT  25 FEB 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Friday's schedules prove vividly the remarkably unchanging nature of much
British television. Sometimes it is a matter of repeats. Captain Scarlet And
The Mysterons (6.00 BBC2) was first screened in 1967 and The Man From UNCLE
which follows is even older: it started in 1965. The late-night sci-fi movie
on Channel 4, Them, (12.05) which has been shown umpteen times on
television, is 40 years old.
Some current series are almost as long in the tooth. The press review, What
The Papers Say (7.45 BBC2) first turned up in 1956; Britain's most popular
drama series, Coronation Street (7.30 ITV) began in 1960; and the science
series Tomorrow's World is in its 30th year (7.30 BBC1).
In BBC2's series about six Manchester students, The Living Soap Colin's 21st
birthday coincides with rag week (7.15). In Olympic Grandstand there is
women's figure skating, ice hockey and ski-jumping on BBC2 (8.00). In Love
Hurts the relationship between sub Sloane Ranger Tessa and rich rough
diamond Frank is getting more, not less, complicated (9.30 BBC1).
