<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / Lack of consensus plagues councils shake-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's attempt to re-draw the map of English local government on
the back of consensus by local politicians looks certain to fail.
In at least nine counties - Cheshire, Cumbria, Essex, Hampshire, Kent,
Lancashire, Nottinghamshire, Suffolk and West Sussex - county councillors
are refusing to agree to abandon the two-tier system of districts and
counties, while district councils want the areas to be carved into
all-purpose 'unitary' authorities.
Pressure from local Conservative MPs could be critical to the outcome in
these areas.
Consensus has been reached on some significant changes. Several cities and
large towns - including Brighton and Hove, Leicester, Milton Keynes,
Stoke-on-Trent and Plymouth - seem certain to become all-purpose
authorities, in a return to the status many once enjoyed as county boroughs.
Several counties - including Bedfordshire, Berkshire, Cambridgeshire,
Dorset, Hertfordshire and Shropshire - also seem certain to abandon the
two-tier structure, although there is still room for disagreement over the
shape of the new unitary authorities.
But the failure of many areas to reach any agreement is bad news for the
government, which aims to set up new authorities for 30 per cent of rural
England by May next year, with the rest to follow in May 1996.
It believes this can only be done if councils present consensus plans to the
Local Government Commission, chaired by Sir John Banham.
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, changed his guidance to Sir John
last September after his plans for the first tranche of counties had met
with fierce criticism from local interest groups. The commission is now to
give priority to locally agreed proposals.
If no agreement can be thrashed out locally the commission and the
government will be left to impose one.
The Association of District Councils supports the government's preferred
position of creating unitary bodies, and has urged its members to agree
mergers. Districts are doing so, although in most counties they are keeping
the number of mergers to a minimum.
The Association of County Councils initially objected to altering the
two-tier structure and now recommends its members to look for new unitary
councils that are as large as possible.
Even counties that are volunteering to split into unitary bodies find
themselves in dispute with local districts. Cambridgeshire, for example, is
in favour of two unitaries, while the districts want five.
Oxfordshire hopes to become one large unitary county, with more power
devolved to towns and parishes, while similar proposals are being explored
by Surrey, where districts have announced plans for five or six unitary
bodies.
Disputes are becoming increasingly acrimonious, with both sets of
authorities accusing their rivals of overspending on publicity and
propaganda. Huntingdonshire District Council and Kent and Surrey county
councils have been accused by local rivals of spending too much on local
'information campaigns'.
Big cities have the strongest case for unitary status, as metropolitan
authorities in London, the West Midlands, South and West Yorkshire and
Manchester and Merseyside are already unitary. Several counties therefore
seem content to allow cities to become unitary, but to keep the rest of the
area unchanged.
Devon is likely to allow Plymouth to become unitary, but will probably call
for a continued two-tier structure for the rest of the county. Staffordshire
and Leicestershire are likely to make similar proposals for Stoke-on-Trent
and Leicester.
Yet districts are unlikely to concur with 'doughnut' agreements, and in
Devon they strongly support creating six new unitary authorities.
In Wiltshire, Thamesdown District Council, which includes Swindon, is likely
to become unitary, while Bournemouth, Luton and Bedford also seem certain to
be part of unitary structures.
But Hampshire is holding out against even a 'doughnut' arrangement and wants
Portsmouth and Southampton to stay within the two-tier system for the rest
of the county.
Support is growing among several counties and a few districts, such as
Congleton in Cheshire, for compromising by reforming the two-tier structure
to remove anomalies and transfer some powers to the districts. The argument
is that this could achieve many of the benefits of reorganisation without
the costs and confusion.
The ACC's vice-chair, Ms Josie Farrington, believes that this could be
achieved within the commission's legal framework. But Mr David Curry, the
local government minister, believes improvements to the two-tier system are
disallowed by the legislation which framed the review.
The ADC strongly backs Mr Curry. Mrs Margaret Singh, the chairman, said
'minor grace and favour' concessions from the counties would be
unacceptable.
With compromises hard to find, the government may soon be in the position it
wanted most to avoid - arbiter of an increasingly heated struggle between
entrenched interests.
</TEXT>
<XX>
