FT  25 FEB 94 / Tecs attack budget scheme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A government initiative that aims to improve local regeneration schemes has
been criticised by training and enterprise councils as a 'missed
opportunity' for business and job creation.
Employer-led Tecs are among several organisations, including local
authorities, that will be encouraged to bid for the new Single Regeneration
Budget (SRB) which will, from April, replace 20 separate economic
regeneration programmes at present run by five government departments.
Tecs, which administer government training programmes in England and Wales,
have the additional responsibility of spearheading local economic
development. A large part of their economic development budgets will be
subsumed by the new SRB.
Tecs fear that in spite of the different budgets being pulled together into
the SRB, the focus of most of the programmes will remain that of alleviating
deprivation, especially physical and social problems in inner cities. Mr
Edward Roberts, chairman of the Tec National Council, said yesterday: 'While
we accept that improving the physical environment helps to facilitate
growth, we are urging the government to change its draft SRB proposals to
place much greater emphasis on increasing competitiveness, business growth
and skills, and on the physical developments which will support this.'
Strict guidance for SRB bids has been drafted by the government and this has
caused some conflict with Tecs.
</TEXT>
