<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / Directors warned on legal liabilities
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Non-executive directors of UK companies may not appreciate that their
personal legal liability 'may have substantially increased', a senior
British industrialist warned last night.
Sir Owen Green, recently retired chairman of the industrial conglomerate
BTR, told an audience in London that the 1992 Cadbury report on corporate
governance does not have the force of law, but 'it will have legal
consequences'.
Sir Owen explained that its attempt to create what he called a 'half-way
house' between unitary and two-tier boards 'must create legal confusion'. In
the event that the courts are involved in any issues of governance 'they
will take the (Cadbury) code as representing the reasonable requirements of
directors'.
The strength of the old legal distinction between executive and
non-executive directors may have been diluted, perhaps extinguished, in the
case of members of audit, remuneration and nomination committees.
In setting out his personal corporate governance vision - at odds in many
respects with the Cadbury approach - Sir Owen strongly criticised the role
of auditors and renewed his earlier attack on excessive executive pay.
He said a review of the auditing profession was 'well overdue' and that
auditors' independence from company managements must be restored. This could
be done by making any change in auditors subject to a special or
extraordinary meeting, while limited liability should also be considered.
'Restore his role as professional watchdog - but not bloodhound,' he said.
On pay, Sir Owen called for disclosure of all benefits of high-paid
executives. 'The Cadbury suggestion of remuneration committees of
non-executive directors is demonstrably not a solution.'
Cadbury critique, page 14
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
