<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / Shareholders 'must see option scheme benefit'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BARRY RILEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Executive share option schemes must be perceived to offer something to
shareholders as well as to managers, National Association of Pension Funds
delegates were told yesterday, Barry Riley writes.
Last month the association controversially expressed 'strong disapproval' of
the share option scheme since implemented by the investment group M&amp;G. Mr
Angus Matheson, the association's investment committee chairman, yesterday
praised the 'efforts and ingenuity' of several big companies such as Reuters
and Grand Metropolitan in framing their more complex proposals.
Instead of schemes linked simply to the share price - such as the M&amp;G
arrangement - institutional shareholders are now expecting companies to
relate the options to some more sophisticated measure of corporate
performance, such as beating an index.
The association, along with the Association of British Insurers, has for
some time been pressing for executive share options to be subject to
shareholder-oriented guidelines.
But Mr Matheson said that, judging by the responses by companies to the
association's consultative document on the subject, corporate respondees'
level of understanding of share schemes was 'disappointing to say the
least'.
Mr Geoff Lindey, who is about to become investment committee chairman, said
the decision on an appropriate performance yardstick was up to the company.
</TEXT>
