<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / SIB plans split of safety funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Financial services companies will no longer have to bail out companies in
other sectors of the industry that are unable to meet their liabilities to
investors, under new arrangements published yesterday by the City's chief
watchdog.
The proposals from the Securities and Investments Board will mean an end to
present arrangements for the investors' compensation scheme, under which
costs - up to a liability of Pounds 100m a year - are met by a levy on all
the firms which are members of the self-regulating organ-isations.
The ICS offers a safety net for investors who are entitled to redress but
find that the firm responsible for their predicament has gone out of
business.
The paper underlines SIB's aim of withdrawing from direct regulation of
firms. It says that those firms which it does regulate will be treated for
the purposes of the compensation scheme as though they belonged to the
appropriate self-regulating organisation.
Since this decision was the most controversial of the proposals, it offers
further evidence that SIB is determined that even firms that are not
enthusiastic should have as little choice as possible about joining the new
regulator for retail financial services, the Personal Investment Authority.
Cross-contribution has been a contentious issue in the industry. Under the
new ICS arrangements each self-contained fund will have a limit of Pounds
100m for its potential liability to claims.
Assuming the PIA comes into existence there will be three funds, one for PIA
members, one for members of Imro, the self-regulating organisation for the
fund-management industry, and one for the Securities and Futures Authority,
the self-regulating body for private-client stockbrokers.
The date for the introduction of the new 'stand-alone' funds will depend on
when the PIA becomes operational, which is expected to be in mid-July.
</TEXT>
