<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / Rules set for price-sensitive data
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Stock Exchange yesterday released guidance for companies to use in
communicating price-sensitive information to the marketplace, intended to
aid compliance with the insider-trading rules in the new Criminal Justice
Act.
The rules take effect next week.
The exchange said it would discuss with the Treasury a more specific
definition of what constitutes creating a 'false market' for share dealing,
because market participants believe the current definition is too broad and
vague.
The guidance was developed by the exchange and a panel that included
representatives of shareholder groups, securities analysts and the 100 Group
of finance directors.
Mr Martin Hall, the exchange's director of policy, said: 'This is not a
clampdown of information. It is intended to improve the flow of information
into the market.'
Mr Hall said the panel took the view that the faster price-sensitive
information was made available to the marketplace, the less the opportunity
for insider dealing.
He said the exchange did not intend to take steps to see to it that
companies followed the guidance. 'We are not obliging people to observe
this,' he said. The exchange hoped that 'people should observe the spirit of
this and it should not be seen as a bonanza to lawyers'.
The panel stopped short of forming a definition of what constituted
price-sensitive information, saying that it would have to include too many
variables to come up with a consistent standard.
The panel also considered, but rejected, suggestions that companies be
required to issue quarterly trading statements similar to those required in
the US. Mr Hall said: 'It is not part of our scheme of things to present a
push towards quarterly reporting. There was very strong resistance to
another formal regulatory burden.'
Companies are, however, urged to make statements about trading conditions at
regular intervals.
The exchange clarified what a company's obligation is to analysts who make
forecasts about profits. There is no obligation to tell individual analysts
that their forecast is wrong and if companies do so they must immediately
inform the markets generally. An analyst hearing such a forecast is required
to inform the Stock Exchange which, in turn, will ask the company to make a
statement.
Companies ought, however, to make public announcements quickly when they
realise their own forecasts of sales or profits are misleading.
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
                             MAIN POINTS
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Companies should have a consistent procedure for determining what
information is sufficiently significant for it to be price-sensitive
and for releasing that information
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Companies should consider making their internal communications
policies known publicly
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Companies should make arrangements to keep price-sensitive information
confidential until it is announced, and must not allow this information
to leak
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Companies are urged to have a structured communications plan with
regular updates on their trading position and immediate prospects
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Where companies issue lengthy releases either to shareholders or to the
market as a whole which include comments or future trading prospects,
this information should be given due prominence
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
A holding announcement should be used where a company and its advisers
believe that there is a danger of information about an unexpected or
significant event leaking where the facts cannot be confirmed
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
If price-sensitive information is inadvertently released a company
should take immediate steps to ensure that the whole market has access
to the same information
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
A company should correct a public forecast as soon as possible if the
outcome is significantly different
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Companies should not be drawn into correcting incorrect price-sensitive
information or assumptions
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
Companies should be prepared to give a 'no comment' answer where
journalists are pressing for price-sensitive information. Where there is
a risk that sufficient price-sensitive information has been collected
for a story to be broadly accurate, a company should ensure the proper
information is widely available
 ----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Services &amp; Services use.
    TECH  Safety &amp; Standards.
</TP>
