<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / From knee-cappings to normality: Michael Cassell goes on
patrol with the RUC Shankill unit in Belfast, where officers face chilling
experiences
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL CASSELL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sgt Ian McKeown points through the bullet-proof windscreen of his patrol car
to a graffiti-smeared sculpture at the heart of west Belfast's Hammer
estate. 'Looks fair enough by day. But at night, this is where the boys get
a bullet through the knee or the calf,' he says.
A Royal Ulster Constabulary colleague, crammed in the back of the sergeant's
battered blue Escort, explains that the victims turn up by appointment for
punishment after offending their paramilitary minders. Not to appear would
result in an even messier fate.
'There's one who is supposed to have telephoned the ambulance before he set
out, telling them what time to get there,' he says.
Humour, at first, might not seem entirely appropriate in such sickening
circumstances but its importance quickly becomes apparent as Sgt McKeown -
which is not his real name - proceeds with his extraordinary job.
As leader of the nine-strong Shankill patrol unit he has an important role
in the 350-strong team based behind fortress walls at Tennent Street police
station. It is responsible for a territory which offers a cocktail of
everyday urban normality and calculating, murderous extremism. One minute a
driving offence or a 'domestic', the next a car hijacking or a punishment
beating.
Tennent Street's patch includes about three square miles of west and north
Belfast, predominantly Protestant territory squeezed into a wedge bordered
on both sides by republican ghettoes. The IRA launches sorties from the
Ardoyne and the Falls while volunteers from the loyalist Ulster Freedom
Fighters and Ulster Volunteer Force take their orders from command centres
on the Highfield estate and the lower Shankill.
Protestant and Roman Catholic paramilitaries pass in the night, launching
raids into each other's areas. The RUC is caught in the middle, hated not
only by the provos but by the loyalists too if they think it is doing its
job too well.
The Tennent Street subdivision has seen 280 murders since the troubles began
more than 20 years ago, 11 of them last year. Nine of those deaths were in
the Shankill Road fish and chip shop bombing last October. Sgt McKeown was
among the first on the scene.
'Someone said there was a secondary device but no one cared. We had to get
them out. It was total chaos,' he recalls quietly. The signatures of 3,200
local people later thanked the police for what they did on that grisly
Saturday afternoon.
None of Tennent Street's officers have been killed since 1987, though a
colleague from a neighbouring area died last week - the first RUC victim of
this year - after a rocket attack in Friendly Street.
Everyone is horrified, though 293 RUC officers have died on the streets of
Northern Ireland since 1969 and people are no longer so easily shocked. Supt
Charlie Robinson, Sgt McKeown's boss, has carried two RUC colleagues to
their graves.
Armed with his Ruger revolver and weighed down by body armour, the sergeant
remains philosophical about the risks. He stresses that his job is as much
about the everyday task of community policing as it is about nailing
paramilitaries. He drives slowly past the derelict Lawnbrook social club,
one-time base for the murderous 'Shankill butchers' of the 1970s. The
surviving gang members got jail sentences totalling 2,000 years.
Sgt McKeown knows by sight a lot of the hard men. As Supt Robinson puts it:
'We stop them all the time. They know you and they know you know them. We
have to treat them absolutely correctly, until we catch them at it.'
The sergeant also knows all the alleyways and short-cuts and can match
endless locations to countless atrocities: 'That's where a young mother was
gunned down in the chemist's shop' - 'A Royal Irish Regiment man was killed
there with an assault rifle on his way to visit his mother.'
On the Crumlin Road he points out the grounds of a chapel, used by the IRA
to launch a recent rocket attack on a police vehicle. 'They stick packets of
digestive biscuits in the back end (of the rocket launcher) to absorb the
shock waves. Can't buy the damn things anywhere in the Ardoyne'.
He checks out an old cottage on the upper Crumlin where a woman was kept
hostage overnight to ensure her businessman husband handed over cash to
terrorists. 'Have to be careful here. It could be wired up. Wouldn't want to
buy it.'
Sgt McKeown stops in Ligoneil, a republican enclave on his beat, to watch an
army 'rummage search' on wasteland for a weapons cache or culvert bombs.
'Almost certainly find something around here, it's a favourite spot.'
So why does he do it? His pay packet bulges from endless overtime and is
further fattened by the Northern Ireland allowance - 'danger money in any
other language'. He has a pride in his work, a great 'crack' with his
colleagues, but above all he wants law and order and decency to prevail on
the streets where he was born.
Things, believe it or not, are getting better. Crime detection is up and
among the nation's highest. Terrorist prevention measures are working and
the neighbourhood policing strategy is paying dividends.
There are no end of applicants ready to join up. Catholics form only about 8
per cent of the total RUC force. In Tennent Street no one knows how many
there are because no one asks.
'It's a very happy place in many ways,' says Supt Robinson. 'We try to keep
the place as normal as possible.' In April Tennent Street's 20 women
officers will, for the first time, go on patrol armed with guns. In Belfast,
normality is a difficult concept to grasp.
</TEXT>
