<DATE>940225
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / Industry horrified by Malaysian threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and KIERAN COOKE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, KUALA LUMPUR
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Industrialists and bankers were horrified yesterday by the news that the
Malaysian government was planning to cease giving business to British
companies.
A banker involved in financing Malaysian trade said: 'We are doing
everything we can to get the Malaysians to change their minds, otherwise
years of marketing and billions of pounds of potential contracts will go
down the drain.'
The Malaysians will honour existing contracts but there will be no time
limit on the embargo on new business. The banker said the move could be
costly for British companies that were currently negotiating government
contracts worth Pounds 2bn.
A UK-Japanese consortium including Trafalgar House, Balfour Beatty, Gammon
and G-Mats (part of GEC) has signed a memorandum for development and project
management of a new MDollars 13.5bn (Pounds 3.4bn) international airport for
Kuala Lumpur. The initial contract was worth a comparatively modest amount.
The expectation was that bigger contracts would have gone to British
companies. According to a businessman these companies were told yesterday
they would not get any of the more profitable contracts.
British companies including National Grid, PowerGen and Rolls-Royce are
negotiating contracts in Malaysia's fast-expanding power sector.
British construction and engineering companies, including John Laing, Bovis
and John Brown, have won substantial contracts in Malaysia and were hoping
for bigger things as Malaysia geared up to spend millions on infrastructure.
Laing has been negotiating a contract on the construction of a Pounds
200m-plus military base at Mersing.
Dr Mahathir Mohamad, the Malaysian prime minister, has been particularly
incensed by press allegations that he was linked to Malaysian officials who
were allegedly in receipt of bribes.
A leading British businessman said: 'He is sick to death of the press
attacks.' The final straw is said to have been an allegation in the Sunday
Times that a British construction company was paying bribes to politicians
in Malaysia.
Today's statement from the Malaysian government is expected to express
'sympathy' for the UK government and British companies over the behaviour of
the British media.
Dr Mahathir has enormous power and influence in Malaysia. He has been in
power for 13 years. A government adviser said ministers viewed attacks on Dr
Mahathir as attacks on Malaysia.
Australia learned this late last year after an aside by prime minister Mr
Paul Keating which described Dr Mahathir as 'recalcitrant' for not attending
a gathering of Asia Pacific leaders. Malaysia reacted by threatening to
cancel Australian business contracts and to downgrade diplomatic relations.
The affair was resolved after public expressions of regret by Mr Keating.
This will be the second time that Dr Mahathir has launched an embargo on
British trade. In October 1981 he initiated a 'Buy British Last' policy that
was maintained for three years, after the withdrawal of UK government
subsidies for foreign students in Britain.
Dr Mahathir frequently attacks what he feels to be western arrogance -
whether it concerns world trade, the environment or human rights. He said
recently: 'Sometimes you have to be a bit notorious to be a bit famous. In
order to be known you have to be nasty.'
Baroness Thatcher worked assiduously and successfully to rebuild the
relationship with Malaysia. She and Dr Mahatir have a high regard for each
other. Since 1988, when she signed a memorandum of understanding with him on
Pounds 1bn of UK defence sales to Malaysia, British companies have won a
series of profitable contracts.
A banker said: 'Apart from Hong Kong, it's the only country in the Asia
Pacific region where British companies have had significant successes.'
Britain has made an estimated Pounds 1.3bn of defence sales to Malaysia
since 1988 and British companies have won civil projects worth considerably
more than that. British exports to Malaysia have risen from Pounds 227m in
1986 to Pounds 862m last year.
But relations with the British government deteriorated last year because Dr
Mahathir was highly critical of what he viewed as Britain's inadequate
support for Bosnia's beleaguered Moslem community.
A businessman with close links to the Malaysian government said: 'He
lectured John Major about Bosnia for 55 minutes when he saw him last
September.'
Dr Mahathir and his cabinet then became annoyed by criticism in the British
press and parliament that the Pounds 1bn arms deal was won because the
government gave Pounds 234m of aid for the dam at Pergau.
A British businessman said: 'They can't see what all the fuss is about.
After all, they want the dam and it's being built by British companies.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Trafalgar House.
    Balfour Beatty.
    Gammon.
    G-Mats.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>MYZ  Malaysia, Asia.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9721 International Affairs.
    P1629 Heavy Construction, NEC.
    P1542 Nonresidential Construction, NEC.
</IN>
