<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / PM to challenge tax 'mythology'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The prime minister and the chancellor are to launch an onslaught on what
they call the 'mythology' of Tory tax rises in the next few days, as Labour
continues to accuse the government of disguising the impact of tax
increases.
Mr John Major and Mr Kenneth Clarke are determined to counter Labour's claim
that the level of taxation under the Conservatives is greater than it was
under Labour.
Mr Major will emphasise in a speech at the Conservatives' local government
conference on Saturday that tax rises imposed in the last Budget were
intended to reduce the government's budget deficit, while taxation under
Labour simply promoted bigger spending plans.
He will say that the effect of the November Budget will be to take less cash
out of the economy than Labour claims.
The speeches follow a fresh Labour attack on the Budget. Mr John Smith, the
Labour leader, said yesterday that government figures had shown a fall in
real disposable income of the poorest social groups in the past 15 years.
