<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / Commons committee members ask for Pergau letters
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Members of the Commons foreign affairs committee are asking the government
to release two confidential letters which outline why Mr John Major gave the
final approval for a Pounds 234m package of government aid for the Pergau
Dam, James Blitz writes.
The letters, written by Sir Charles Powell, a former adviser both to Mr
Major and Baroness Thatcher, could shed light on why the government
continued with the aid project in spite of vehement objections from Sir
Timothy Lankester, permanent secretary at the Overseas Development
Administration.
The letters came to light in a memorandum written to Sir Timothy in spring
1991 by Mr Douglas Hurd, the foreign secretary. Mr Hurd said he had
'considered carefully' Sir Tim's arguments but had concluded that 'we should
support the project'.
Another document, a protocol signed in March 1988 by Lord Younger, then
defence secretary, expressly links the provision of aid to the Malaysian
government with a projected arms deal. Malaysia received more money under
the British government's Aid and Trade provision scheme last year than any
other country except China, the Foreign Office revealed yesterday. In a
parliamentary answer, the Foreign Office said Malaysia received Pounds
17.798m in 1992-93.
</TEXT>
