<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / Israeli minister expects further drop in jobless
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID HOROVITZ
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JERUSALEM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Unemployment in Israel fell to 9 per cent in the final quarter of 1993 -
giving a full year average of 10 per cent, compared with 11.2 per cent in
1992.
The improvement was hailed by Mr Avraham Shochat, Israeli finance minister,
as vindication of the Labour government's economic policies.
He predicted a further fall in the jobless rate in 1994 to about 9 per cent.
The figures, released by Israel's Central Bureau of Statistics, showed that
101,000 new jobs were created in 1993, an increase of more than 6 per cent
over the previous year.
Analysts attributed the falling jobless totals to three factors:
An increase in Israel's gross domestic product;
Israeli workers in the building trade have replaced many of the 50,000
Palestinians from the occupied territories no longer permitted entry into
Israel;
The slowdown in immigration from the former Soviet Union.
From a low of 6 per cent in 1987, unemployment had been growing steadily
until last year, fuelled by the arrival of hundreds of thousands of Russian
Jews.
A new report issued by the Treasury, meanwhile, predicted 5.6 per cent
growth in Israel's GDP for 1994 - a revision of the 5.3 per cent prediction
in the budget last October.
</TEXT>
