<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / US to host talks on new Bosnia state: Ceasefire prompts west
to act quickly on Moslem-Croat confederation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Bosnian Croat and Bosnian Moslem leaders will meet in Washington at the
weekend for US-sponsored talks aimed at forging a bi-national state in part
of war-torn Bosnia, a top State Department official said last night.
The Zagreb-based Croatian government will also join in the talks, which
spring from US determination to play a pivotal role in the search for peace
in Bosnia.
The move comes as a ceasefire signed by Bosnian Croats and Bosnia Moslem
army commanders is due to come into effect today. The truce mainly affects
central Bosnia but could be expanded to other areas.
Bosnian prime minister Haris Silajdzic had talks with US secretary of state
Warren Christopher in Washington yesterday. Mr Silajdzic said the US was
being 'helpful'.
Under the plans being discussed, Bosnian Croats and the Moslem-led Bosnian
government would incorporate territory westwards and northwards of Sarajevo
into the new entity. The status of Serb-held territories in eastern Bosnia
is being left to separate negotiations.
One of the strengths of the plan is that it gives Croatia and the Moslems a
(face-saving) reason for ending their conflict in part of the republic.
At the same time, the US will be able to support the plan - and the Bosnian
government - providing a pretext for Washington not to commit ground troops
once a peace settlement is signed.
'If both sides agree to the confederation, the peace settlement could be
more benign and require fewer peacekeepers,' one western diplomat said. But
another diplomat disagreed: 'Any ceasefire and peace will require tens of
thousands of peacekeepers.'
The plan could entail transfers of population. 'Each side hates the other so
much. I cannot envisage Moslems and Croats living side by side, for
instance, in Mostar, in the near future,' a diplomat said.
The idea of a confederation has re-emerged for several reasons. First,
Croatia longs for peace, even though President Franjo Tudjman still harks
after his Greater Croatia. The threat of sanctions against Zagreb by the US
and some EU countries has played a role.
Second, the Bosnian prime minister believes the confederation could give the
Moslems access to the sea, and viability as a state.
Third, the plan could be sold to the US as, theoretically, it is seen as
preserving some of Bosnia's territorial integrity and has not been forced on
the Moslems.
The pitfalls are many. Above all, it depends on how the plan is perceived by
President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia, who holds the key to peace.
Croatian President Franjo Tudjman indicated in Zagreb yesterday that if a
Moslem-Croat federation was formed in Bosnia it could become part of a
confederation with Croatia.
In a speech to the central committee of his HDZ party, Mr Tudjman said: 'The
thing would be to have a sort of federation of Croats and Moslems (in
Bosnia) which would be in a confederation with Croatia.'
He went on: 'An alliance with the Moslems would protect the interests of the
West. Moslems would be directed towards Western civilisation, eliminating
the elements who would create a fundamentalist Islamic state in Bosnia.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>BAZ  Bosnia-Hercegovina, East Europe.
    HRZ  Croatia, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
