<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / Futures selling hits European bond and share prices
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CONNER MIDDELMANN, TERRY BYLAND and JOHN PITT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Heavy selling in the futures markets pushed European government bond prices
sharply lower yesterday and sparked a fall in share prices.
UK government bonds, known as gilts, posted the biggest losses, with
longer-dated issues falling by more than 2 1/4 points.
Wednesday's slide in US Treasuries, combined with fears that UK interest
rates would not fall further and could even rise, triggered early selling in
London that was later exacerbated by weakness on the continent. The Liffe
March gilt futures contract dropped by 2 23/32 points to 111 13/16 .
After European markets closed, fresh declines in US Treasury prices prompted
heavy selling of equities in New York, where share prices were already weak
on news that the multi-billion dollar merger between Bell Atlantic and
Tele-Communications had been abandoned.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average finished 51.78 down at 3,839.90. Investors
were unnerved by another big decline in Treasury prices, which pushed the
yield on the benchmark 30-year bond up to 6.738 per cent.
The fall in European bond markets prompted the largest one-day fall in UK
equities for the past 16 months, although trading volume in the stock market
was not unduly heavy. The FT-SE 100 Index fell 74.4 to 3,267.5, closing near
its low for the day. The FT-SE 100 is about 7.7 per cent below its trading
peak of 3,539.2 at the beginning of this month.
Other European government bond markets also fell heavily, with traders
reporting heavy selling by US hedge funds. 'The markets are dominated by
overwhelmingly negative sentiment - looking for rational explanations would
be misleading,' said Mr John Shepperd, chief economist at Yamaichi
International.
Nervousness in the bond mar kets has been sparked by the recent rise in US
short-term interest rates and worries about a pick-up in US inflation.
German government bonds fell sharply on concern at potential turmoil in
Russia and the prospect of unfavourable economic data. The March Bund
futures contract on Liffe had dropped by 1.31 points to 96.65 late in the
afternoon in London.
French bonds also fell sharply after the Bank of France trimmed its
intervention rate by 10 basis points to 6.1 per cent, on disappointment over
the size of the cut. The March French bond futures contract on the Matif
exchange dropped by 1.04 points to 126.94.
In European equity markets, Germany's Dax index of the 30 most traded stocks
lost nearly 2 per cent to 2,090. In France, the CAC-40 index slid about 2
per cent to 2,208.
Lex, Page 24; Bonds, Page 35; Currencies, Page 43; World stocks, Page 49;
London stocks, Page 52; Fixed-rate loans, Page 10
</TEXT>
