<HEADLINE>
FT  25 FEB 94 / Malaysia set to halt UK deals: Mahathir angry at press
reports about tactics used to win contracts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Malaysian government is planning to deny further contracts to British
companies because of its anger at British press reports alleging that bribes
have been offered to Malaysian politicians.
The contracts freeze, which could cost British companies hundreds of
millions of pounds in lost business, was confirmed early today by Mrs
Rafidah Aziz, Malaysia's minister of trade and industry. It was due to be
announced by Mr Anwar Ibrahim, Malaysia's deputy prime minister and finance
minister, although a press conference set for this morning was postponed
until later today.
Last night, Mr John Major sent a message to Dr Mahathir Mohamad, the
Malaysian prime minister, seeking urgent clarification of Malaysia's
position. The Foreign Office was also striving to head off the breakdown in
trade relations.
The sanctions are similar to those imposed under Malaysia's 'Buy British
Last' policy in the early 1980s after Britain withdrew subsidies for foreign
students. They were lifted in the late-1980s after Lady Thatcher, as
premier, worked to rebuild ties with Malaysia.
UK companies, led by GEC, plan to issue a statement - in the form of
national newspaper advertisements - stressing the importance of
Anglo-Malaysian trade. Yesterday they secretly approached Mr Major urging
him to telephone Dr Mahathir.
Dr Mahathir has been angered by UK press reports of the alleged tactics used
by the UK government and UK companies in winning Malaysian contracts. He was
incensed by a report in last weekend's Sunday Times alleging that a British
company had bribed Malaysian politicians, an adviser said.
A banker who knows Dr Mahathir said he had also been bemused by criticism in
the UK parliament and press that a contract to sell Pounds 1bn of arms to
Malaysia was won because the UK gave Pounds 234m in aid for building the
Pergau hydro-electric dam.
Mr Dato Kamarudin Abu, Malaysian High Commissioner in London, said his
government was 'very unhappy about the constant negative reporting'.
Sir Robin Biggam, chairman of BICC, the cable and construction group
involved in the Pergau project, said the ban would be 'a very regrettable
and unfortunate decision for the UK. It has taken us years to build up our
position in Malaysia'.
Malaysia is the biggest market for UK companies in the Asia-Pacific region,
apart from Hong Kong. Exports to Malaysia, most based on contracts with the
Malaysian government, were Pounds 862m in the year to November.
Mr Allan Gormly, chief executive of Trafalgar House, whose construction
subsidiaries have won tens of millions of pounds of Malaysian business,
said: 'This is not only bad for corporate UK but could affect jobs as well.'
Malaysia is expected to say that it will honour existing contracts with
British companies. But a banker who finances Malaysian trade said a stream
of contracts, worth an estimated Pounds 2bn, would now be lost.
Yesterday, the British high commissioner in Malaysia, Mr Duncan Slater, was
told UK companies would receive no further work on a new Pounds 3.4bn
international airport for Kuala Lumpur. An Anglo-Japanese consortium,
including Trafalgar House, BICC and GEC, had signed a memorandum for
development and project management of the airport.
Other leading British companies, such as power groups PowerGen and National
Grid, construction group John Laing and electronics conglomerate GEC, have
been in negotiations with the Malaysian government.
Industry horrified by Malaysian threat, Page 9
Observer, Page 23
</TEXT>
