<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: Equity Futures and Options Trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Stock index futures failed to sustain a rally brought about by demand from
UK institutions and once again closed below the recent support level of
3,350, writes Joel Kibazo.
Having opened at 3,341, the March contract on the FT-SE 100 was actively
sold by leading US houses in the first part of the session, leaving it to
fall to a day's low of 3,329. It was UK buyers that helped to bring a rally
in March and continued demand saw the contract return to trade above its
recent support level by mid-afternoon, reaching a peak of 3,359.
A poor start on Wall Street led to renewed profit-taking until the end of
the session. March finished at 3,338, a small discount to cash and 8 points
below its estimated fair value premium to cash which stands at minus 7 on
this account. Volume at the official close was 15,714 contracts.
Heavy trading in Hanson contributed to an increase in turnover in the traded
options. Total volume was 54,400 lots. The FT-SE 100 option saw business of
15,377 and the Euro FT-SE 100 option 1,336 contracts dealt. In the stock
options, Hanson led the way with 6,468 lots traded, the February 280 calls
being the busiest series. It was followed by Barclays at 2,856 and Tesco at
2,823.
Activity in the FT-SE Mid 250 futures contract traded on the OMLX remained
low, with a mere 188 lots dealt.
</TEXT>
