<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / London Stock Exchange: BAe doubts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PRICE, PETER JOHN, JOEL KIBAZO and STEVE THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A strong initial rise in British Aerospace was checked by sharp profits
downgrades as the market looked towards the near-term prospects for the
group. The shares were up 35 at best but ended the day 9 ahead at 549p after
hefty trading of 7.6m.
BAe reported losses sharply reduced at Pounds 237m, a near 20 per cent jump
in the dividend, favourable cash flow and a lack of surprise write-offs.
However, the analysts' meeting with the company dispersed the euphoria as it
became clear that big losses at the group's commercial aircraft division
were set to continue. BAe also indicated that defence profits were likely to
soften over the next two years.
Long-term bull Strauss Turnbull reduced it current-year forecast by Pounds
35m to Pounds 215m and Paribas cut by Pounds 60m to Pounds 190m. Mr Paul
Compton of Credit Lyonnais Laing came in at the bottom of the range with a
Pounds 165m estimate but remained guardedly optimistic. 'The financial
implications of the recent Rover deal are so significant as to outweigh
trading disappointment,' he argued.
</TEXT>
