<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / International Company News: Canon agrees to use IBM's PC
technology
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Canon, the Japanese camera and office equipment maker, has agreed to use US
computer group IBM's PowerPC microprocessor technology in future computer
products. It will also help refine technology for use in consumer products
and hand-held devices.
The Canon endorsement is a breakthrough for IBM, which aims to establish
PowerPC as an industry standard competing with Intel's microprocessor
technology. Canon is the first computer systems manufacturer, other than
Apple and IBM itself, to adopt PowerPC as a strategic technology.
The agreement does not entail Canon incorporating PowerPC in its printers,
cameras or copying machines.
</TEXT>
