<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / International Company News: SA engineer edges ahead
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MATTHEW CURTIN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Contracts related to three large capital projects and exports to China
helped Murray &amp; Roberts (M&amp;R), the South African engineering and
construction group, offset difficult local trading conditions in the
half-year to December 1993. Pre-tax profit edged forward to R180m (Dollars
51m) from R178m in 1992.
Sales climbed 13 per cent to R3.7bn, as the group's engineering and
materials divisions picked up work on the Alusaf smelter expansion, Columbus
Stainless Steel expansion and Nawakwa Sands projects. Mr Andre van der
Colff, chief executive, said M&amp;R would reap the full benefit of its
involvement in the projects by the year-end.
He said the group continued to export successfully, supplying engine blocks
to Volkswagen South Africa for a R900m order from China, valves for a Hong
Kong/China water pipeline, and seatbelts for a US motor manufacturer.
M&amp;R's exposure to reconstruction spending has made its shares popular among
foreign investors buying South African equities. The shares closed unchanged
at R84.75 yesterday, near their R86 high 10 days ago.
Income before interest and depreciation charges rose to R377m from R340m,
before higher interest payments of R60m against R43m. A lower tax bill
flattered after-tax income, but distributable profit slid to R107m from
R111m. Earnings fell 3 per cent to 171 cents from 177 cents a share.
Mr van der Colff said despite falling operating margins, tight cost controls
were improving the group's cash generation - operating cash flow per share
rose to 363 cents from 255 cents - which lay behind the decision to increase
the interim dividend by 2 cents to 58 cents. It would be an 'exceptional'
achievement, given South Africa's unsettled political and economic climate,
for the group to claw back the earnings decline by the year-end.
</TEXT>
