   LISBON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Banco Portugues de Investimento (BPI), Portugal's leading investment bank,
registered a 42 per cent drop in consolidated net profits last year,
compared with 1992, to Es8.1bn (Dollars 46m).
Mr Artur Santos Silva, BPI president, attributed the fall in profits to a 29
per cent reduction in the margin between loans and deposits, and a
substantial increase in provisions from Es3.8bn in 1992 to Es8.3bn last
year.
BPI, which wholly owns the privatised retail bank Banco Fonsecas e Burnay,
partly compensated for a slow 3 per cent growth in consolidated credit with
a 22 per cent rise in commission-based earnings and a 59 per cent increase
in profits from financial operations, mainly government debt security
trading.
Secil, a Portuguese cement producer due for privatisation later this year,
has announced a 5.5 per cent increase in profits in 1993 to Es4bn. Sales
remained virtually unchanged at Es22bn.
