<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Spurs shares dip to 82p on profits downturn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER PEARSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Shares in Tottenham Hotspur, the north London football club now 50.1 per
cent owned by Mr Alan Sugar, its chairman, fell 10p to 82p yesterday on news
that pre-tax profits for the six months to November 30 had fallen from
Pounds 3.28m to Pounds 644,000.
However, Mr Colin Sandy, finance director, said profits on continuing
operations before interest rose from Pounds 242,000 to Pounds 275,000.
Meanwhile a case brought by Tottenham for winding-up Edennote, a company
controlled by Mr Terry Venables, Spurs' ousted chief executive and team
manager, was yesterday adjourned until April, as Mr Venables plans to fight
the petition.
Mr Sandy said Tottenham had sought the winding-up over Pounds 335,000, which
was the adjudication by the taxing master of money owed from a possible
Pounds 400,000. This, plus a further Pounds 150,000 of costs over Mr
Venables' claim for wrongful dismissal as chief executive last summer were
provided for in last year's accounts.
The Football Association is still investigating the club over player
transfer dealings, but Mr Sandy said Mr Rick Parry, Premier League chief
executive, did not expect the club to be relegated.
Turnover fell to Pounds 12.3m (Pounds 15.1m) as the proceeds from the
disposal of players' registrations fell to Pounds 4.54m (Pounds 8.15m). The
figure was boosted by Pounds 2.8m from the Pounds 5.5m sale of Paul
Gascoigne.
Interest payable was Pounds 86,000 (receivable Pounds 352,000, including
Pounds 450,000 from the Gascoigne sale). Earnings per share tumbled to 2.7p
(19.2p). There is no interim dividend.
