<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Only the vows will satisfy the sceptics -
Why the float of 3i is again being proposed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER and RICHARD GOURLAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If the promised wedding between institutional investors and 3i, the UK's
leading provider of equity finance to small and medium-sized businesses, is
finally held this summer it will mark the end of one of the most prolonged
and turbulent courtships the stock market has ever known.
The suggestion that the six clearing banks and the Bank of England which own
3i - formed in 1945 as the Industrial and Commercial Finance Corporation -
may finally float up to 40 per cent of its equity provokes some natural
scepticism. The notion of a float has been around for up to a decade.
Yet the banks, led by National Westminster and Barclays, which between them
own 41 per cent of 3i's equity, have good reason to support a 3i float now.
'There is hardly going to be a better time. It is just common sense really,'
said a director of one of the shareholding banks yesterday.
The last attempt to float 3i early in 1993 came to grief because National
Westminster and Barclays decided that they would not gain enough from
selling their stakes. Although 3i's net assets had risen to Pounds 1.3bn by
then, the sale price was not likely to be sufficiently attractive.
This is because NatWest, which holds a 23.1 per cent stake, is among
shareholders which equity account for 3i. This allows them not only to gain
from 3i dividends but from the rise in net asset values. This is thought to
add about Pounds 15m a year to NatWest profits, in addition to the dividend
income.
This means that the float price for 3i becomes a delicate calculation. Banks
such as NatWest have to gain enough from the one-off sale of part of their
stakes in return for giving up regular income. The loss would be more
pronounced if it prevented them from equity accounting their stakes.
Accordingly, the rise in the shares of venture capital investment trusts -
the most obvious comparison being Electra - over the past year was very
significant.
The sector discount to net asset values has now fallen to about 11 per cent,
compared with a historic high of 35 per cent.
The most immediate benefit of a flotation for the shareholders is that 3i
will gain investment trust status. At the moment it is classed by the Inland
Revenue as an investment company and is required to pay corporation tax on
profits made from the sale of assets.
Once 3i floats as an investment trust, there will be no corporation tax
liability on the sale of investments and group shareholders' funds will be
that much better off.
As to the size of the float, 3i's advisers, Baring Brothers, and
shareholders are understood to have chosen to sell no more than a third of
the company in order to avoid the substantially greater cost involved in a
larger sale like that of Wellcome shares last year.
The float nevertheless left some of the venture capital industry somewhat
uneasy. Some venture capital groups which are raising new capital are having
an exceptionally difficult time persuading UK institutions to replenish
their funds.
Institutions may have decided not to invest in these new funds in order to
enter the unquoted company sector indirectly via the 3i flotation.
3i added further to the competition for funds earlier this month when for
the first time it raised a Ecu300m (Pounds 227m) fund of its own. 'There is
no doubt potential investors were attracted by the spread of our business
and the enormous deal flow we enjoy,' said Mr Ewen Macpherson, 3i chief
executive.
3i denies the move into fund management has anything to do with the float.
But it is clearly planning to raise further fee-earning funds, possibly for
investment in the UK.
Such a move would inevitably drain funds that might have flowed to the
venture capital groups already focused on investing in smaller unquoted
companies.
By raising funds 3i will also be able to keep more of the deals it finds and
has to syndicate because of its policy of only taking minority stakes in its
investments.
3i could therefore become a significantly less generous provider of deals to
smaller venture capital groups. This is likely to lead to further pressure
for consolidation among the smaller venture capital suppliers within the
industry.
So will 3i change its approach to its market once it becomes a quoted
company and an FT-SE 100 stock to boot?
'We are not going to shorten the time horizons for our investments,' says Mr
Charles Richardson, director of corporate affairs. One of 3i's selling
points, it says, is that it does not push companies to provide investors
with an exit, unlike many other venture capital providers.
A company's management is the 'best judge' of when to seek a float or a
trade sale, 3i says. But the 3i flotation will give it greater flexibility
to sharpen its focus on the smaller unquoted investment sector.
The group is considering, for example, setting up a venture capital
investment trust or regional venture capital trust along the lines proposed
by the chancellor in the last budget. This depends on details of the trusts
which the Treasury expects to announce by the end of the month.
Aside from the financial calculations, the shareholder banks decided that 3i
had reached the stage where it should benefit from the financial discipline
of a Stock Exchange listing. They regarded the group as having reshaped
itself in a way that would withstand investor scrutiny.
Despite the financial and managerial logic, the engagement has been mooted
so long that there will be a sceptical City audience until the vows are
finally exchanged.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>3i.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6799 Investors, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
