<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / UK Company News: Survey finds optimism among smaller
companies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PEGGY HOLLINGER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain's smaller companies are bullish about growth prospects in the short
term, in spite of looming tax increases which some have speculated could
hinder economic recovery.
A survey by brokers SG Warburg showed that 74 per cent of companies expected
an improvement in the economy over the next 12 months.
This contrasts sharply with recent public opinion polls, which showed that
only 13 per cent of respondents expected an improvement.
The survey also showed that more companies felt there had been no change in
the timeliness of invoice payment, which was widely considered to be poor.
About Pounds 50bn is estimated to be outstanding on overdue invoices in the
UK. Some 58 per cent of companies questioned favoured the introduction of
statutory interest on late payments. About a third opposed legislation.
The survey, A View From the Boardroom, was based on the responses of 448
chairmen and chief executives of companies with market values of less than
Pounds 300m.
It is Warburg's first attempt to track comprehensively the views of senior
executives in the smaller companies sector. The survey, conducted in January
and February, will be produced on a three or four-monthly basis.
Companies were found to be more optimistic than just three months ago, with
46 per cent of those surveyed saying order books were between 1 per cent and
10 per cent ahead in that period. About a third of companies said orders had
remained static. Two thirds said they expected sales to increase over the
next three months.
The economic growth expected by UK companies is unlikely to mean a change in
employment levels, however.
The consumer goods sector was less optimistic than either the manufacturing
or service industries. This contrasts with recent statistics showing a pick
up in consumer spending.
Some 39 per cent of consumer goods companies reported that import
penetration of their UK markets had 'increased a little'.
Mr Richard Hickinbotham, head of Warburg's smaller companies research team,
said the findings of the survey 'are particularly bullish for small
companies' earnings prospects'.
However, to justify further outperformance in an already buoyant small
company sector, 'we need to see the results of the survey reflected in
company statements and ultimately in meaningful earnings advances', Mr
Hickinbotham said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9611 Administration of General Economic Programs.
    P6231 Security and Commodity Exchanges.
</IN>
