<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / The Lex Column: UK gilts
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
After the turbulence of the last week, the Bank of England must be glad to
have got yesterday's gilts auction away successfully. But if the cover of
1.5 times looks respectable, the six basis point difference between the
average and the lowest accepted yield leaves room for doubt about the
strength of demand. It looks as though cover was boosted by a number of
rogue bids submitted on the off chance of picking up paper on the cheap.
With overseas demand at a low ebb, it did not help that the Chancellor's
panel of independent advisers was lukewarm about further interest rate cuts
on Tuesday. That sapped confidence at the short end of the market, while Mr
Alan Greenspan's soothing words to Congress have not yet fully calmed
sentiment at the longer end of international markets. At some stage, the
positive fundamentals should draw buyers out again. After all, inflation is
low and at least one more cut in UK rates remains in prospect. Gilts' 70
basis point yield premium over US Treasury issues is a good starting point
for a recovery. But it may take a while to make itself felt.
</TEXT>
