<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / IoD urges end to 'enterprise deficit'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LUCY KELLAWAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Britain is suffering from an 'enterprise deficit' according to the Institute
of Directors, which called yesterday for a rethink of the role of companies
and directors in the economy.
In a consultation document published yesterday the IoD argues that, in the
debate on corporate governance, too much emphasis has been placed on the
integrity of directors while the question of how best to promote enterprise
has been neglected.
Lord Young, IoD president and chairman of Cable and Wireless, said the
Cadbury report on corporate governance had limited itself to the behaviour
of directors whereas it was more important to 'get the wealth aspect first'.
'Enterprise without integrity is the motto of the Mafia. Integrity without
enterprise is the principle of nationalised industries. What we need is a
combination of both.'
The report argues that the enterprise deficit - the absence of innovation,
investment and risk-taking by companies - is partly responsible for the poor
international standing of Britain's economy. 'Future improvement in British
economic performance requires more new UK companies to be established and
more existing companies to grow,' the report says. It adds that this is
needed to balance the dominance of large quoted companies in the economy.
As the government increasingly loosens the contraints on business, the onus
rests with directors to ensure that they are running their companies in a
competent and professional manner, the document says.
It questions whether boards of directors are capable of supplying enterprise
on the scale the economy requires. It argues for a role for non-executive
directors that is more dynamic than the controlling role spelled out in the
Cadbury report.
Mr Peter Morgan, director-general of the IoD, said the IoD rejected the idea
that non-executives were watchdogs. 'They should be round the table bringing
new skills. You get the watchdog role for free. What you want them for is
what they can contribute.'
The document lays down four main functions for boards of directors. These
are: to set the strategic direction of the company, to make sure that
strategy is being implemented, to monitor executive management and to
provide information. It argues that all directors should take part in all
these tasks.
In setting directors' pay, the report states there should be no pay-offs for
failure, and that objectivity and openness are essential in determining what
compensation executives deserve.
The paper is part of an IoD initiative to associate itself more closely with
the needs of directors, as well as with its better known function as a
lobbying body. Earlier this week, the IoD published a draft set of standards
covering the composition and behaviour of boards.
Enterprise with Integrity. IoD, 116 Pall Mall, London SW1T 5ED. Free.
Observer, Page 25
</TEXT>
