<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Self-regulation of press sought
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Association of British Editors, the Guild of Editors and the
International Press Institute yesterday launched a document detailing the
case against new legal restrictions on the media.
In the document - Media Freedom and Media Regulation - the three
organisations identify 46 statutes which they say inhibit reporting, list
the media's self-regulation measures and argue that there are potential
dangers in further restrictions on the public's right to know.
Mr James Bishop, ABE chairman, says in his preface to the document that
'there is continuing difficulty in reconciling the individual's right to
privacy and the public's right to know.
'But the legal constraints already in place, together with the latest steps
in self-regulation, provide sufficient protection of privacy and are more
than adequate to meet current parliamentary concern.'
The document was drafted by Prof Hugh Stephenson, professor of journalism at
London's City University, after a meeting of more than 60 newspaper,
magazine, radio and television editors last autumn.
The meeting followed pressure for legislation to make invasion of privacy a
civil wrong, and the replacement of the present system of press
self-regulation centred on the Press Complaints Commission.
The paper gives examples of news items it believes could have been barred by
legislation, including coverage of the Lyme Bay canoeing disaster, reports
of the acceptance of a foreign holiday from a prominent Palestinian by Mr
David Mellor, former heritage secretary, World in Action's investigation of
the Birmingham Six and the publication of Mr Michael Mates's letter to Mr
Asil Nadir.
Mr Bishop said self-regulation had been developing all the time. 'We believe
it is now working very effectively.'
Privacy legislation could not stop abuses, he said. 'There are laws against
murder but murders still happen.' Self-regulation meant editors sitting down
together to try to prevent any problems.
</TEXT>
