<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Race body aims to boost impact
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Commission for Racial Equality yesterday announced a new structure aimed
at making better use of its resources and meeting Citizen's Charter
standards.
Commission staff will be deployed to work more closely with other agencies
as part of a 'promotional drive throughout society'.
Mr Herman Ouseley, commission chairman, said racial discrimination was
'subtle, covert and sophisticated'. The restructuring was intended to make
the commission more responsive and effective, and to bring it closer to its
clients - both the institutions that came to it for guidance and the victims
of discrimination.
Under its Citizen's Charter undertakings the commission will set standards
for handling inquiries - for example acknowledging letters in two working
days and providing full replies in a further eight.
With resources limited and a budget unlikely to increase in real terms in
the near future, members of the commission believe greater collaboration
with other agencies offers the best chance of increasing the commission's
influence.
The commission is campaigning with other race relations bodies for stronger
laws. Members of the Commons home affairs committee are investigating racial
attacks and have been considering whether there should be a new specific
offence of racial violence or racial harassment.
</TEXT>
