<HEADLINE>
FT  24 FEB 94 / Portillo defends curb on spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury, yesterday underlined
his determination to push ahead with the government's long-term review of
public spending in spite of accusations from some Tory backbenchers that the
project is being quietly shelved.
Mr Portillo told the Oxford Union yesterday that the government was
determined to pursue its 'root and branch' examination of the spending
policies of Whitehall departments, questioning the direction programmes were
taking and whether every aspect of the money spent was fully justified.
He said: 'Without a rigorous approach to planning and management there is a
real danger of public spending rising inexorably as a share of GDP. If
spending rises as a share of national income, either taxes must rise or
borrowing must rise, or both.'
Mr Portillo welcomed the results of fundamental reviews last year in social
security, health, education and at the Home Office.
He said eight more reviews were under way in areas such as transport, the
legal departments, Customs and the Treasury.
Some Tory backbenchers were concerned yesterday that - in spite of Mr
Portillo's assurances - the government had not cut departmental budgets with
the rigour called for in the first four reviews.
A senior Tory MP said: 'There is a great deal of scepticism, not about
Michael Portillo, but about whether anything will come from this whole
process. The reviews are referred to as a crutch whenever ministers are
under pressure, but nothing ever seems to happen.'
He rejected a claim by Mr Portillo yesterday that a restructuring of social
security spending announced in the review had been successfully implemented
in the last Budget.
Another backbencher said the reform of statutory sick pay arrangements and
the increased targeting of benefits were 'already in the pipeline before the
last Budget'.
He added that an important test of the government's convictions would be
whether it was prepared to cut the legal-aid budget in the forthcoming
review of legal departments.
Mr Portillo was keen yesterday to reject another criticism of the last
Budget, that cuts in departmental spending were brought about by using the
emergency reserve.
He said that money was used in the Budget 'not to boost expenditure
programmes but to cut government borrowing'. He added that it had always
been spent in previous Budgets, implying that it was wrong for anyone to
suggest otherwise.
</TEXT>
